# 

## Discussion {#discussion}

### Results Interpretation {#results-interpretation}

The evaluation indicates that the Playground delivers its core promise as a learning-first, zero-install “mission sketcher”. Computational checks against standard texts show numerically sane outputs for canonical scenarios (e.g., circular/elliptical orbits and Hohmann transfers), with the mechanics engine behaving stably over typical educational time horizons (Bate, Mueller and White, 1971; Curtis, 2013; Vallado, 2013). These results justify using the tool to build intuition and to illustrate the link between geometric change and underlying dynamics.

On the design side, interface choices were derived from established HCI and learning principles: progressive disclosure and details-on-demand; nested validation at the task/encoding/algorithm levels; and explanatory overlays for “why/why-not” reasoning. Together, these elements are expected to reduce extraneous cognitive load and support dual-channel processing, particularly when paired with concise, well-placed textual cues (Shneiderman, 1996; Munzner, 2009; Ko and Myers, 2004; Sweller, 1988; Mayer and Moreno, 2003; Paivio, 1991).

Finally, the export and integration stance credibly sketches a bridge from learning to professional workflows: GMAT/poliastro/CSV/TLE exports allow the same scenarios to be taken forward for more in-depth analysis without reinventing the work, even if complex missions will still require manual refinement (Hughes and Conway, 2017; Cano Rodríguez and Martínez Garrido, 2022).

### Gap Resolution Analysis {#gap-resolution-analysis}

**G1 On-ramp:** Guided flows and scenario scaffolding provide an approachable starting point that mirrors familiar, game-like interaction while introducing formalism stepwise. The URL-share model supports quick distribution in teaching contexts. (Shneiderman, 1996.)

**G2 HCI:** Progressive disclosure, density controls, and consistent interaction patterns are grounded in CLT and HCI literature and should reduce interface overhead compared with professional tool baselines (Sweller, 1988; Oviatt, 2006; Norman, 2013).

**G3 Teaching:** Explanatory overlays and plain-language tooltips directly target the “why/why-not” gap, coupling visual states with short, adjacent explanations to avoid split attention (Ko and Myers, 2004; Mayer and Moreno, 2003).

**G4 Hand-off:** Export pathways (GMAT script, JSON for poliastro, CSV ephemerides, TLE) establish credible transfer into professional environments for the covered scenario classes. End-to-end verification on real ephemerides remains future work (Hughes and Conway, 2017; Cano Rodríguez and Martínez Garrido, 2022).

**G5 Accessibility:** Cognitive accessibility is treated as a first-class requirement: density/focus controls, reduced-motion and large-text modes, and keyboard/screen-reader support align with current guidance (Gartland et al., 2022; Norman, 2013). The design is expected to benefit all users, not only neurodivergent learners.

**G6 Time-to-insight:** Immediate visual feedback and lightweight flows shorten the path from opening the app to obtaining a meaningful result, consistent with dynamic queries and overview-first patterns (Shneiderman, 1996). Performance targets (initial load \~2.3 s; steady \~60 FPS on modest hardware) support this goal.

### Methodological Contributions {#methodological-contributions}

The work contributes a practical methodology for solo technical projects: chunk-and-nibble planning, explicit dependency maps, ADRs for decision traceability, and documentation-driven development. This approach maintains academic traceability (what was done, why, and with what consequences) while keeping cognitive demands manageable; useful for neurodivergent researchers but likely beneficial more broadly (Nygard, 2011; Anderson, 2010; Boehm, 1988).

Visual documentation (Appendices E1–E9) substantiates the system’s adherence to accessibility and educational-technology design principles, providing tangible evidence of progressive complexity management.

### Limitations and Future Work {#limitations-and-future-work}

**Evaluation scope:** No human-participant studies were conducted; claims are limited to analytic validity, design-theoretic alignment, and plausibility via persona walkthroughs. A small, ethics-approved pilot is the immediate next step (pre/post concept tasks, SUS/UMUX-Lite, NASA-TLX, short interviews) to quantify learning and usability effects (Bangor, Kortum and Miller, 2008; Hart and Staveland, 1988; Lewis, Utesch and Maher, 2013).

**Physics scope:** The proof-of-concept is deliberately constrained to two-body/patch-conic modelling with light perturbations; complex dynamics, finite burns, and operations-grade fidelity are out of scope and should be handed off to professional suites (Curtis, 2013; Vallado, 2013).

**Export scope:** Export has been designed for mainstream cases; full end-to-end verification on real mission ephemerides, and for multi-manoeuvre constellations/tours, remains conceptual (Hughes and Conway, 2017; Cano Rodríguez and Martínez Garrido, 2022).

**Performance:** Browser-first delivery prioritises accessibility over peak performance; native or worker-heavy variants may be required for high-fidelity or complex real-world scenarios.

## 

## Conclusion {#conclusion}

### Project Achievement Summary {#project-achievement-summary}

The project delivers a working, browser-based astrodynamics Playground with validated orbital calculations, progressive-disclosure UI, explanatory overlays, shareable scenarios, and professional exports. Within its patch-conic envelop it behaves predictably and responsively, providing a credible bridge from intuition building to professional workflows (Bate, Mueller and White, 1971; Curtis, 2013; Vallado, 2013; Hughes and Conway, 2017).

### Research Contributions {#research-contributions}

**Educational technology:** A concrete pattern for making high-cognitive-load STEM topics approachable without abandoning rigour: overview-first \+ dynamic queries, minimal density by default, and concise, adjacent explanations (Shneiderman, 1996; Mayer and Moreno, 2003).

**Astrodynamics education:** A practical “on-ramp” that connects Kerbal-style intuition to GMAT/poliastro workflows through exports and shared scenario state, suitable for teaching and early-concept studies (Hughes and Conway, 2017; Cano Rodríguez and Martínez Garrido, 2022).

**Accessibility:** An accessibility-first implementation focused on cognitive load management (density/focus, reduced motion, large text, keyboard/screen reader), reflecting evidence-based mitigations for cognitive barriers (Gartland et al., 2022; Norman, 2013).

**Methodology:** A replicable solo-research workflow (chunking, ADRs, documentation-driven development) that preserves auditability while fitting MSc constraints (Nygard, 2011; Anderson, 2010; Boehm, 1988).

### Future Research Directions {#future-research-directions}

1. **Empirical validation:** Run a small, ethics-approved pilot using pre/post concept inventories, SUS/UMUX-Lite, and NASA-TLX to quantify learning, usability, and workload; iterate overlays and density controls from the findings (Bangor, Kortum and Miller, 2008; Hart and Staveland, 1988; Lewis, Utesch and Maher, 2013).

2. **Export verification:** Move from “export-ready” to “export-proven” by validating complete scenarios against and with real ephemerides in GMAT/poliastro and documenting tolerances (Hughes and Conway, 2017; Cano Rodríguez and Martínez Garrido, 2022).

3. **Scenario width:** Add advanced topics (e.g., gravity-assist, low-thrust sketches, constellation layout) with clear limit guardrails, indicating when to transition to specialist tools (Curtis, 2013; Vallado, 2013).

4. **Accessibility expansion:** Extend beyond ADHD/autism-oriented supports to dyslexia/dyscalculia-aware patterns and richer semantic descriptions for 3D content (Gartland et al., 2022).

5. **Performance paths:** Explore worker offloading/native builds for heavier use cases, while keeping the browser path for teaching and quick studies.

### Closing Reflection {#closing-reflection}

This project began with recognition that astrodynamics education faces an accessibility crisis; powerful professional tools intimidate newcomers, while engaging games lack rigorous foundations. The Astrodynamics Playground represents one attempt to bridge this divide through deliberate, theory-informed design choices that prioritise learner needs.

The development process itself became a case study in accessible research practice. Managing complex technical work as a solo researcher with ADHD required developing new methodological approaches that externalised cognitive load and provided clear progress markers. That these same principles (chunking, visualisation, progressive complexity) appear in both the methodology and the resulting software suggests deep connections between how we work and what we create.

While empirical validation remains essential future work, the series of UI examples (Appendices E1–E9) collectively demonstrate how theoretical design commitments were translated into a functioning educational interface.

The Astrodynamics Playground stands as a proof-of-concept—imperfect, limited, but functional. It demonstrates that complex STEM tools can be reimagined with accessibility at their core rather than as an afterthought.

### Appendix A \- Source Code (GitHub) {#appendix-a---source-code-(github)}

**Repository: [https://github.com/sirnax/astrodyn](https://github.com/sirnax/astrodyn)**  
Version: v1.0.0  
Language stack: TypeScript / React / Next.js 14 / Three.js (R3F) / Tailwind CSS / Jest

**Hosted: [https://astrodyn.vercel.app/](https://astrodyn.vercel.app/)**

Full implementation source code of *Astrodynamics Playground*, an MSc educational technology project enabling interactive 3D orbital-mechanics learning. Built with TypeScript, React (Next.js 14), and Three.js. Includes physics solvers, accessibility features, and analytical validation tests (C1–C5). All calculations verified against *Curtis (2013)* and *poliastro*.

### Appendix B \- Glossary of Terms {#appendix-b---glossary-of-terms}

Selection focuses on domain-specific terms that a general reader may not know.

| Term | Plain-English definition | Reference |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| **ADR (Architecture Decision Record)** | Lightweight notes capturing the “why” behind key technical choices. | Nygard (2011); Parnas & Clements (1986) |
| **Apoapsis / Periapsis** | Farthest / nearest point of an orbit around a body (for Earth: apogee / perigee). | Curtis (2013) |
| **Astrodynamics** | The study of how spacecraft and celestial bodies move under gravity; the physics behind orbits and transfers. | Vallado (2013); Curtis (2013) |
| **Base64 encoding** | Text-safe encoding used to pack binary/structured data into URLs or files. | — |
| **Causal/“Whyline” overlays** | Explanations embedded in tools that answer “why/why not” to improve understanding. | Ko & Myers (2004) |
| **Co-design / “Nothing about us without us”** | Involving target users (incl. disabled/neurodivergent) throughout design and evaluation. | Charlton (1998) |
| **Cognitive accessibility** | Designing interfaces to support diverse attention, memory, and processing needs. | Gartland et al. (2022) |
| **Cognitive Load Theory (CLT)** | Explains how limited working memory constrains learning; designs should reduce “extraneous” load. | Sweller (1988); Kirschner, Sweller & Clark (2006) |
| **CSV / JSON** | Common data formats for tabular data (CSV) and structured objects (JSON). | — |
| **Dynamic queries** | Interactive controls (sliders, filters) that update views instantly to aid exploration. | Shneiderman (1996) |
| **ECI / ECEF** | Earth-Centred Inertial (non-rotating) vs Earth-Centred Earth-Fixed (rotating with Earth) coordinate frames. | Vallado (2013) |
| **Ephemeris** | A time-stamped table of positions (and often velocities) of a spacecraft/body. | Vallado (2013) |
| **Formative vs summative evaluation** | Formative: improve during development; Summative: judge after completion. | Creswell & Plano Clark (2018) |
| **GMAT** | NASA’s General Mission Analysis Tool for professional-grade mission design/propagation. | Hughes & Conway (2017) |
| **Hohmann transfer** | The most fuel-efficient two-burn transfer between two circular, coplanar orbits. | Bate, Mueller & White (1971); Curtis (2013) |
| **Human-Computer Interaction (HCI)** | The discipline of designing/evaluating interfaces so people can use complex systems effectively. | Norman (2013); Oviatt (2006) |
| **J2 oblateness** | Correction to account for Earth’s equatorial bulge that slowly twists orbits. | Vallado (2013) |
| **Keplerian elements** | Six numbers that define an orbit’s size, shape, and orientation (e.g., semi-major axis, eccentricity, inclination, RAAN, argument of perigee, true anomaly). | Vallado (2013); Curtis (2013) |
| **Lagrange points** | Balanced-gravity “parking spots” in a two-body system, useful for observatories and relays. | Vallado (2013) |
| **Multimedia learning principles** | Guidance on combining words, diagrams, and animations to reduce overload and aid learning. | Mayer & Moreno (2003); Paivio (1991) |
| **N-body dynamics** | A fuller model that considers gravitational effects from many bodies at once. | Vallado (2013) |
| **NASA-TLX** | Standard workload measure capturing mental/physical demand, effort, etc. | Hart & Staveland (1988) |
| **Neurodivergent / ADHD-aware** | Recognising and designing for cognitive differences (e.g., ADHD working-memory/attention profiles). | Martinussen et al. (2005) |
| **Orbital mechanics** | Practical application of astrodynamics to plan, analyse, and control spacecraft orbits. | Curtis (2013); Vallado (2013) |
| **Patched-conic approximation** | Method that “stitches” multiple two-body arcs together when moving between planets/moons. | Bate, Mueller & White (1971); Curtis (2013) |
| **poliastro** | Open-source Python library for orbital mechanics with plotting and analysis tools. | Cano Rodríguez & Martínez Garrido (2022) |
| **Progressive disclosure** | UI pattern: show essentials first, reveal details on demand to avoid overload. | Shneiderman (1996); Norman (2013) |
| **RAAN** | Right Ascension of the Ascending Node—sets where an orbit crosses the equator going north. | Vallado (2013) |
| **React / Three.js** | Web frameworks for building interfaces (React) and real-time 3D graphics (Three.js). | — |
| **Scrum / Kanban** | Agile methods for iterative work (time-boxed sprints vs continuous flow/visual WIP limits). | Schwaber & Sutherland (2020); Anderson (2010) |
| **Serialization / Deserialization** | Saving complete app state to a compact format and restoring it later (e.g., shareable URLs). | — |
| **Sphere of Influence (SOI)** | Region around a body where its gravity dominates a spacecraft’s motion. | Vallado (2013) |
| **STK** | Commercial suite (Systems Tool Kit) for trajectory/mission analysis and visualisation. | Blanco (2020) |
| **SUS** | 10-item System Usability Scale for quick overall usability scores. | Brooke (1996); Bangor, Kortum & Miller (2008) |
| **Think-aloud protocol** | Participants narrate thoughts while using a system to reveal usability issues. | Norman (2013) |
| **TLE (Two-Line Element set)** | Standard compact format used to share/propagate Earth-satellite orbits (e.g., SGP4). | Vallado (2013) |
| **Two-body problem** | A simplified model that considers only a spacecraft and one attracting body. | Bate, Mueller & White (1971) |
| **UMUX-Lite** | Two-item alternative to SUS for rapid usability assessment. | Lewis, Utesch & Maher (2013) |
| **Vis-viva equation** | Formula linking a spacecraft’s speed to its distance from the attracting body and orbit size. | Vallado (2013) |
| **Visualisation design model** | A staged approach (problem → tasks → encodings → algorithms) for rigorous vis design. | Munzner (2009) |
| **Working-memory limit** | Typical capacity limits that motivate concise explanations and stepwise interfaces. | Cowan (2001) |
| **ΔV (Delta-V)** | The “push” a spacecraft needs—change in speed required for a manoeuvre; a fuel proxy. | Curtis (2013) |

const generateExplanation \= (parameter: string) \=\> {  
 let content \= '';  
 let type: 'tip' | 'warning' | 'insight' | 'law' \= 'tip';  
 let icon \= \<Lightbulb className\="h-4 w-4" /\>;

 switch (parameter) {  
   case 'altitude':  
   case 'semiMajorAxis':  
     if (characteristics.altitude \< 150) {  
       content \= "⚠️ This altitude is too low for a stable orbit...";  
       type \= 'warning';  
       icon \= \<AlertCircle className\="h-4 w-4" /\>;  
     } else if (characteristics.altitude \> 35786 &&  
                Math.abs(characteristics.altitude \- 35786) \< 100) {  
       content \= "🛰️ This is near geostationary orbit altitude (35,786 km)...";  
       type \= 'insight';  
       icon \= \<TrendingUp className\="h-4 w-4" /\>;  
     }  
     break;  
 }

 setExplanation({  
   isVisible: true,  
   content,  
   type,  
   icon  
 });  
};

#### D2. State-Machine Implementation {#d2.-state-machine-implementation}

**File: components/tutorial-system.tsx**

\`\`\`typescript  
interface TutorialState {  
 activeTutorial: string | null;  
 currentStep: number;  
 completedSteps: Set\<string\>;  
 isVisible: boolean;  
}

const nextStep \= () \=\> {  
 const tutorial \= TUTORIALS\[tutorialState.activeTutorial as keyof typeof TUTORIALS\];  
 if (\!tutorial) return;

 const currentStepData \= tutorial\[tutorialState.currentStep\];  
 const newCompleted \= new Set(tutorialState.completedSteps);  
 newCompleted.add(currentStepData.id);

 if (tutorialState.currentStep \< tutorial.length \- 1) {  
   setTutorialState(prev \=\> ({  
     ...prev,  
     currentStep: prev.currentStep \+ 1,  
     completedSteps: newCompleted  
   }));  
 } else {  
   completeTutorial();  
 }  
};

export function exportMissionData(  
 elements: OrbitalElements,  
 format: 'gmat' | 'stk' | 'json' | 'csv'  
): { data: string; filename: string } {

}

#### D6. Mechanics Engine {#d6.-mechanics-engine}

Implements the physics calculations for two-body propagation, Kepler’s equation solving, Hohmann transfer computation, and limited perturbation modelling.

**File: lib/orbital-mechanics.ts**

\`\`\`typescript  
export function solveKeplerEquation(  
 meanAnomaly: number,  
 eccentricity: number,  
 tolerance: number \= 1e-8,  
 maxIterations: number \= 50  
): KeplerSolverResult {  
 let M \= meanAnomaly % (2 \* Math.PI);  
 if (M \< 0) M \+= 2 \* Math.PI;

 let E \= M \+ eccentricity \* Math.sin(M);  
 let iterations \= 0;  
 let error \= tolerance \+ 1;

 // Newton-Raphson iteration  
 while (iterations \< maxIterations && Math.abs(error) \> tolerance) {  
   const f \= E \- eccentricity \* Math.sin(E) \- M;  
   const fPrime \= 1 \- eccentricity \* Math.cos(E);

   if (Math.abs(fPrime) \< 1e-12) break;

   const delta \= f / fPrime;  
   E \= E \- delta;  
   error \= delta;  
   iterations\++;  
 }

 return {  
   eccentricAnomaly: E,  
   iterations,  
   error: Math.abs(error),  
   converged: Math.abs(error) \<= tolerance  
 };  
}

export function calculateHohmannTransfer(  
 initialRadius: number,  
 finalRadius: number  
): TransferResult {  
 const transferSMA \= (initialRadius \+ finalRadius) / 2;

 const v1Initial \= circularVelocity(initialRadius);  
 const v1Transfer \= orbitalVelocity(initialRadius, transferSMA);  
 const v2Transfer \= orbitalVelocity(finalRadius, transferSMA);  
 const v2Final \= circularVelocity(finalRadius);

 const deltaV1 \= Math.abs(v1Transfer \- v1Initial) \* 1000;  
 const deltaV2 \= Math.abs(v2Final \- v2Transfer) \* 1000;  
 const totalDeltaV \= deltaV1 \+ deltaV2;

 const transferTime \= orbitalPeriod(transferSMA) / 2;

 return {  
   deltaV1,  
   deltaV2,  
   totalDeltaV,  
   transferTime,  
   phase: 180 \* (1 \- transferTime / orbitalPeriod(finalRadius)),  
   burnTime1: new Date(),  
   burnTime2: new Date(Date.now() \+ transferTime \* 1000),  
   explanation: generateTransferExplanation(...)  
 };  
}  
\`\`\`

#### D10. Export Module (GMAT Integration) {#d10.-export-module-(gmat-integration)}

Generates annotated GMAT-ready mission scripts containing spacecraft definitions, manoeuvre sequences, propagators, and validation comments.

**File: lib/education-utils.ts**

\`\`\`typescript  
function generateGMATScript(elements: OrbitalElements): string {  
 const { semiMajorAxis, eccentricity, inclination, raan, argumentOfPeriapsis, trueAnomaly } \= elements;

 return \`%----------------------------------------  
%---------- Spacecraft  
%----------------------------------------

Create Spacecraft DefaultSC;  
GMAT DefaultSC.DateFormat \= UTCGregorian;  
GMAT DefaultSC.Epoch \= '${elements.epoch.toISOString()}';  
GMAT DefaultSC.CoordinateSystem \= EarthMJ2000Eq;  
GMAT DefaultSC.DisplayStateType \= Keplerian;  
GMAT DefaultSC.SMA \= ${semiMajorAxis};  
GMAT DefaultSC.ECC \= ${eccentricity};  
GMAT DefaultSC.INC \= ${inclination};  
GMAT DefaultSC.RAAN \= ${raan};  
GMAT DefaultSC.AOP \= ${argumentOfPeriapsis};  
GMAT DefaultSC.TA \= ${trueAnomaly};

%----------------------------------------  
%---------- Propagators  
%----------------------------------------

Create ForceModel DefaultProp\_ForceModel;  
GMAT DefaultProp\_ForceModel.CentralBody \= Earth;  
GMAT DefaultProp\_ForceModel.PointMasses \= {Earth};

Create Propagator DefaultProp;  
GMAT DefaultProp.FM \= DefaultProp\_ForceModel;  
GMAT DefaultProp.Type \= RungeKutta89;

%----------------------------------------  
%---------- Mission Sequence  
%----------------------------------------

BeginMissionSequence;

% Propagate for one orbital period  
Propagate DefaultProp(DefaultSC) {DefaultSC.ElapsedDays \= 1};

% Generated by Astrodynamics Playground  
% Visit: ${window.location.origin}  
\`;  
}  
\`\`\`
